Remove the upper triangle of data (The data is repeated so it isn’t important)


get_upper_tri <- function(cor_wine){
    cor_wine[lower.tri(cor_wine)]<- NA
    return(cor_wine)
}

reorder_cor_wine <- function(cor_wine){
# Use correlation between variables as distance
dd <- as.dist((1-cor_wine)/2)
hc <- hclust(dd)
cor_wine <-cor_wine[hc$order, hc$order]
}

Random Forest Model

Run a random forest model. From the graph we can see that this model is better at predicting if a bottle of wine is high quality.


wine_rf <- randomForest(quality ~ .,
                       data = wine_clean,
                       type = classification,
                       mtry = 4,
                       na.action = na.roughfix,
                       ntree = 100, 
                       importance = TRUE)

print(wine_rf)

Tune the random forest model to determine what the optimal parameters (mtry) are. From the graph we can see that an mtry of 7 would give us the least amount of error


rf_mods <- list()
oob_err <- NULL
test_err <- NULL
for(mtry in 0:11){
  rf_fit <- randomForest(quality ~ ., 
                         data = wine_clean,
                         mtry = mtry,
                         na.action = na.roughfix,
                         ntree = 20)
  oob_err[mtry] <- rf_fit$err.rate[20]
  
  cat(mtry," ")
}

results_DF <- data.frame(mtry = 1:11, oob_err)

Now if we rerun the random forest model with an mtry of 2 the error has decreased compared to the above model with a mtry of 4.
